As of the [[census]]{{GR|2}} of 2000, the population comprised 173,618 people, 62,389 households, and 35,859 families.<ref name=census/> The [[population density]] was 3,629.4/km¬≤ (9,401.7/sq&nbsp;mi), characteristic of comparatively older cities in [[New England]] such as [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], [[Connecticut]], [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], and [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], [[Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/44/4459000.html | title=Providence (city) QuickFacts from the US Census Bureau|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate = 2007-01-18}}</ref> Also like these cities, its population peaked in the [[1940]]s just prior to the nationwide period of rapid [[suburbanization]]. Providence has had a substantial Italian population since the turn of the century, evidenced by its own Little Italy in [[Federal Hill, Providence, Rhode Island|Federal Hill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceri.com/Neighborhoods/fedhill.html providenceri.com|publisher=City of Providence|title = Federal Hill|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref>  Irish immigrants have also had considerable influence on the city's history, with 8% of residents claiming Irish heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/genealogyInfo.php?locIndex=13448|title=Providence &mdash; Ancestry & Family History|accessdate=2007-06-19|publisher=ePodunk Inc.}}</ref>

Belying Providence's traditionally white makeup is the sizable minority presence it has acquired in the last twenty years. Though nearby cities like Boston and Hartford have longer-standing black and Latino communities, Providence now has a higher minority percentage, with non-Hispanic whites comprising less than half (45.8%) of the population.<ref name=demographics>{{cite web|url=http://www.provplan.org/Matriarch/MultiPiecePage.asp?PageID=54&PageName=InfoDataPeopleDemographics provplan.org|publisher=The Providence Plan|title=Information and Data &mdash; People & Demographics|accessdate=2007-06-06}}</ref><ref name=hispanic>{{cite web|url=http://www.rifoundation.org/matriarch/documents/latino_1_2%281%29.pdf|format=PDF|title = Geographic Concentration of the Latino Population|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> Though salient contributions to this growth have been among Asians and unspecified races, the most dramatic change comes from Hispanics, whose presence has increased fivefold.<ref name =hispanic/> Having origins in [[Puerto Rico]], [[Colombia]], the [[Dominican Republic]], and [[Central America]] (particularly [[Guatemala]]), Hispanics have strong influence in the neighborhoods of [[Elmwood, Providence, Rhode Island|Elmwood]], the [[West End, Providence, Rhode Island|West End]], and [[Upper South Providence, Providence, Rhode Island|Upper]] and [[Lower South Providence, Providence, Rhode Island|Lower South Providence]].<ref name=hispanic/>  Hispanic impact is even larger in the city's schools. Hispanics represent over half (55%) of all students in the city's school system while comprising only 30% of Providence's population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sreb.org/programs/hstw/publications/case_studies/05V05_Providence.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Southern Regional Education Board|pages=2|title=The Providence Public School Department and The University of Rhode Island Partnership|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref><ref name=demographics/>

In addition, Providence, like nearby [[Fall River, Massachusetts]] and [[New Bedford, Massachusetts]], has a considerable population of immigrants from the [[Portuguese Empire]], living mostly in the areas of Washington Park and [[Fox Point, Providence, Rhode Island|Fox Point]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceri.com/Neighborhoods/foxpoint.html providenceri.com|title=Fox Point|publisher=City of Providence|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://204.17.79.244/profiles/wpk_bk.html provplan.org|title=Washington Park|publisher=The Providence Plan|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bosfed.org/commdev/c&b/2004/Fall/Immigrants.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of Boston|title=Who are New England's Immigrants?|author=Manie Marcuss and Ricardo Borgos|page=4|accessdate=2007-06-06}}</ref>  [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]]s constitute approximately 15% of the city with the largest percentages in [[Mount Hope, Providence, Rhode Island|Mount Hope]] and Upper and Lower South Providence neighborhoods.<ref name=racebyplace>{{cite web|url=http://204.17.79.244/profiles/cw_mrpeo.html provplan.org|publisher=The Providence Plan|title=Maps & Rankings: People|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref><ref name = census/>  [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asians]] are 6% of Providence's population and have enclaves scattered thoroughout the city.<ref name=racebyplace/> Another 6% of the city has multiracial ancestry.  Native Americans and Pacific Islanders make up the remaining 1.3%.<ref name=census/>

The [[Providence metropolitan area]], which includes Providence, [[Fall River, Massachusetts|Fall River]], [[Massachusetts]], and [[Warwick, Rhode Island|Warwick]] is estimated to be 1,622,520.<ref name=metro/> In 2006, this area was officially added to the Boston Combined Statistical Area (CSA), the [[Table of United States Combined Statistical Areas|fifth-largest CSA in the country]].  In last fifteen years, Providence has experienced a sizable growth in its under-18 population, attributed to the influx of Hispanics.<ref name=demographics/> The median age of the city is 28 years, while the largest age [[Cohort (statistics)|cohort]] is comprised of 20 to 24 year olds owing to the city's large student population.<ref name=demographics/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://providence.areaconnect.com/statistics.htm providence.areaconnect.com|publisher=MDNH, Inc.|title=Providence Population and Demographics|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref> 

The [[per capita income]], as of the [[United States Census, 2000|2000 census]], was $15,525, which is well below both the state average of $29,113,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infoplease.com/ipa/A0104652.html infoplease.com|publisher=HighBeam Research, LLC|title=Per Capital Personal Income by State|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> and the national average of $21,587.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/2002pubs/c2kprof00-us.pdf|format=PDF|title=U.S. Summary: 2000|pages=4|accessdate=2007-06-10|publisher=US Census Bureau}}</ref><ref name=census/>  The median income for a household was $26,867, and the median income for a family in Providence was $32,058, according to the 2000 census.  The city has one of the highest rates of poverty in the nation with 29.1% of the population and 23.9% of families living below the [[poverty line]] in 2000, the largest concentrations being found in the city's [[Olneyville, Providence, Rhode Island|Olneyville]], and Upper and Lower South Providence areas.<ref name=povmap>{{cite web|url=http://204.17.79.244/profiles/cw_mrecon.html provplan.org|title=Maps & Rankings: Economics|accessdate=2007-06-10|publisher=The Providence Plan}}</ref><ref name=poverty/> Poverty affected children at a disproportionately higher rate with 40.1% of those under the age of 18 living below the poverty line, concentrated particularly west of [[Downtown, Providence, Rhode Island|downtown]] in the neighborhoods of [[Hartford, Providence, Rhode Island|Hartford]], [[Federal Hill, Providence, Rhode Island|Federal Hill]], and Olneyville.<ref name=povmap/>

===Crime===
The rate of violent crime in the city has dropped for five consecutive years, running contrary to contemporaneous national trends in comparably-sized cities.<ref name=sharply>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/Prov_Homicides21_01-21-07_HF3VCSS.18cf2e9.html|publisher=Providence Journal|title=Violent crime falls sharply in Providence|accessdate=2007-06-11|author=Gregory Smith}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rwu.edu/newsandevents/news/policechiefs051507.htm|title=Providence Police and Roger Williams Co-Host Conference on Reducing New England's Violent Crime|Publisher = Roger Williams University|accessdate=2007-06-11}}</ref> The city's 11 homicides in 2006 represented a historic low.<ref name=sharply/> Averaged over three years, murders had highest concentrations in Olneyville and the West End neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://204.17.79.244/profiles/tables/crime/pvdnhoodcrime02_04.pdf|format=PDF|title=murder|publisher=The Providence Plan|accessdate=2007-06-11}}</ref> Of the 239 United States cities over 100,000 in population, Providence's violent crime rate ranked 84th in 2003, as compared with New York City at 94th and Boston at 28th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.provplan.org/Matriarch/MultiPiecePage.asp?PageID=52&PageName=InfoDataCrimePublicSafety|title=Crime & Public Safety: Crime in Providence|publisher=The Providence Plan|accessdate=2007-06-11}}</ref> Notwithstanding its comparatively low rate of violent crime, Providence has the fifth-highest rate of property crime per 100,000 inhabitants in the country,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://finance.yahoo.com/insurance/article/104025/America's-Most-Jealous-Cities|title=America's Most Jealous Cities|publisher=Forbes.com|accessdate=2007-12-14}}</ref> which is 50% above the national average, with car theft in particular at 150% higher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityrating.com/citycrime.asp?city=Providence&state=RI|title=Providence Crime Statistics (RI)|publisher=cityrating.com|accessdate=2007-06-11}}</ref>

[[David Cicilline]], mayor since [[2002]], is a member of the [[Mayors Against Illegal Guns Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mayorsagainstillegalguns.org/html/about/members.shtml| title=Mayors Against Illegal Guns: Coalition Members|publisher=Mayors Against Illegal Guns|accessdate=2007-06-17}}</ref> a [[bi-partisan]] group with the goal of reducing illegal gun ownership. The Coalition is co-chaired by [[Boston]] Mayor [[Thomas Menino]] and [[New York City]] Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]].

==Economy==
Providence was one of the first cities to industrialize in the United States. By 1830, the city had manufacturing industries in metals, machinery, textiles, jewelry, and silverware. Though manufacturing has declined, the city is still one of the largest centers for [[jewellery|jewelry]] and [[Silver (household)|silverware]] design and manufacturing. Services, particularly education, health care, and finance, also make up a large portion of the city's economy. Providence also is the site of a [[Sectional center facility (SCF)|sectional center facility]], a regional hub for the U.S. Postal Service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actonelists.com/resources/zip.html|title=
Sectional Center Facility Chart |publisher=Act One Lists|accessdate=2007-06-16}}</ref> Since it is the capital of Rhode Island, Providence's economy additionally consists of government services.

[[Image:Prov-econ.JPG|right|350px|thumb|Data from City-Data.com<ref>{{cite web | title = Providence Economy | publisher = Advameg Inc. | work = City-Data.com | date = 2007 | url = http://www.city-data.com/us-cities/The-Northeast/Providence-Economy.html | accessdate = 2007-03-13}}</ref>]]
