[[Image:Providencetextronside.JPG|thumb|[[Textron Tower|Textron's headquarters]], [[Sovereign Bank Tower (Providence)|One Financial Plaza]], and the Rhode Island Hospital Trust building]]The Fortune 500 conglomerate [[Textron]] and Fortune 1000 company Nortek Incorporated are both headquartered in the city, and [[GTECH]]'s world headquarters has recently been moved to downtown Providence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtech.com/media/fact_sheet.asp?persist=8C934E72427B4F958B9C876926B4BE4A|publisher=GTECH Corporation|title= GTECH Corporation - Company Fact Sheet|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref> [[Citizens Financial Group|Citizens Bank]] is also headquartered in Providence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizensbank.com/au/history.aspx Citizens Bank - History|publisher=Citizens Financial Group|title= Ownership and History|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref>  Another company whose origins were in the city is [[FleetBoston Financial|Fleet Bank]]. Once Rhode Island's largest bank, it moved its headquarters to [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], after acquiring Shawmut Bank in 1995. Before its acquisition by [[Bank of America]], Fleet merged with [[BankBoston]] to become New England's largest commercial bank.

The city is home to the Rhode Island Convention Center, which opened in December 1993.<ref name=convention>{{cite web|url=http://www.riconvention.com/why_us/ricc_whyus.html riconvention.com|publisher=Rhode Island Convention Center|title=Rhode Island Convention Center - About Us?|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref> Along with a hotel, the convention center is connected to the [[Providence Place|Providence Place Mall]], a major retail center, through a [[skywalk]].<ref name=convention/> The Port of Providence, the second largest deepwater [[seaport]] in New England,<ref name=economy/> handles cargo such as cement, chemicals, heavy machinery, petroleum, and scrap metal.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.provport.com/about.html | title=About Us | publisher=ProvPort, Inc. - Port of Providence | year=2007 | accessdate = 2007-03-01}}</ref>

==Government==
[[Image:Providencecityhall.jpg|thumb|Providence City Hall in the [[Second Empire|Second Empire Baroque]] style]]
[[Image:RIstatehouse.JPG|thumb|[[Rhode Island State House]] at sunset]]
Providence serves as Rhode Island's capital, housing the [[Rhode Island General Assembly|Rhode Island Legislature]] as well as the offices of the [[Governor of Rhode Island|Governor]] and the [[Lieutenant Governor of Rhode Island|Lieutenant Governor]] in the [[Rhode Island State House]].

Providence's city government has a [[Mayor-council government|mayor-council]] form of government. There are fifteen city councilors, one for each of the city's wards. The city council is tasked with enacting ordinances and passing an annual budget. Providence also has probate and superior courts. The [[U.S. District Court for the District of Rhode Island]] is located downtown across from City Hall adjacent to Kennedy Plaza.

[[David N. Cicilline]] was elected mayor by a large margin in 2002 and was re-elected without any major opposition in 2006. Cicilline is the first openly [[gay]] mayor of an American state capital.<ref name=firstmayor>{{cite journal | author= Dahir, Mubarak| url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1589/is_2002_Dec_24/ai_95916251 |title=Leading Providence: David Cicilline becomes the first openly gay mayor of a U.S. state capital - Politics | journal=The Advocate| publisher=FindArticles|date=[[December 24]] [[2002]] | accessdate = 2007-01-20}}</ref> Providence is the largest American city to have an openly gay mayor.<ref name=firstmayor/>

{{see also|List of foreign consulates in Providence}}

==Education==
===Postsecondary===
[[Image:Manning Chapel.jpg|right|thumb|Hope College and Manning Hall at Brown University]]Seven of the fourteen institutions of higher learning in Rhode Island have campuses in Providence (city proper):
*[[Brown University]], an [[Ivy League]] university
*[[Community College of Rhode Island]] (Downcity and Liston campuses) 
*[[Johnson & Wales University]], notable for culinary program, considered one of the best such programs in the world
*[[Providence College]], a Catholic school, one of the top master‚Äôs level colleges in the northeast United States and a member of the [[Big East Conference]].
*[[Rhode Island College]]
*[[Rhode Island School of Design]] (RISD), one of the country's top art colleges
*[[University of Rhode Island]] (Providence campus). 

Between these schools the number of postsecondary students is approximately 44,000, or 25% the population of Providence.<ref>This figure is calculated as the sum of individually given figures from school websites, see: {{cite web|url=http://www.brown.edu/web/about/facts/ brown.edu|title=facts about Brown University|publisher=Brown University|accessdate=2007-06-05}}, {{cite web|url=http://www.ccri.edu/About/general.shtml|publisher=Community College of Rhode Island|title=General Information about CCRI|accessdate=2007-06-05}} (Note: exact figures for Providence Campuses were unavailable. For this estimate two fifths of the total student body were approximated to go to two of the five campuses_, {{cite web|url=http://www.johnsonandwales.edu/prov/index.htm johnsonandwales.edu|title=Johnson & Wales Providence|publisher=Johnson & Wales University|accessdate=2007-06-05}}, {{cite web|url=http://www.providence.edu/About+PC/Fast+Facts/ providence.edu|title=Providence College - Fast Facts|publisher=Providence College|accessdate=2007-06-05}}, {{cite web|url=http://www2.ric.edu/aboutRIC/ ric.edu|title=about RIC|publisher=Rhode Island College|accessdate=2007-06-05}}, {{cite web|url=http://www.risd.edu/aboutrisd.cfm risd.edu|title=RISD: About RISD|publisher=Rhode Island School of Design|accessdate=2007-06-05}}, and {{cite web|url=http://autocrat.uri.edu/1346.html uri.edu|publisher=University of Rhode Island|title=About US|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref>  Compounded by Brown University's being the second-largest employer,<ref name=economy/> higher education exerts in a considerable presence in the city's politics and economy.

===Private and charter schools===
Several private schools, including [[Moses Brown School|Moses Brown]], the [[Lincoln School, Rhode Island|Lincoln School]], and the [[Wheeler School]], are in the city's [[East Side, Providence, Rhode Island|East Side]]. [[La Salle Academy, Providence|La Salle Academy]], a Catholic high school, is located in the Elmhurst area of the city near Providence College. The public charter schools [[Time Squared Academy High School|Times Square Academy]] (K-12) and Textron Chamber of Commerce (9-12) are funded by GTECH and [[Textron]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceschools.org/dept/news/files/9E0BC30F74514CA18DB979D75C88BEBF.pdf|format=PDF|title=The Providence Public School District at a Glance|publisher=Providenceschools.org|accessdate=2007-06-11}}</ref> In addition, the city's South Side houses Community Preparatory School, a private school serving primarily low-income students in grades 3-8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communityprep.org/htm/1story.htm communityprep.org|publisher=Community Preparatory School |title=About CPS|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref>

===Public schools===
The [[Providence Public School District]] serves about 26,000 students from pre-Kindergarten to grade 12. The district has 25 elementary schools, nine middle schools, and thirteen high schools. The Providence Public School District features [[magnet school]]s at the middle and high school level, Nathanael Greene and [[Classical High School|Classical]] respectively. There are two centers for students with special needs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceschools.org/dept/students/index.html|publisher=Providence Schools|title=About the Student Body|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref>

==Culture==
[[Image:Providence20June07ProvidenceTheaterB.jpg|thumb|The Providence Performing Arts Center]]
{{seealso|Media in Providence}}
Much of Providence culture is synonymous with [[Rhode Island#Culture|Rhode Island culture]]. Like the state, the city has a [[non-rhotic]] accent which can be heard on local media. Providence also shares Rhode Island's propensity for coffee, as the former has the most coffee/doughnut shops per capita of any city in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urbanplanet.org/forums/lofiversion/index.php/t5597.html |title=Chewing over why we love doughnut shops|author=Patinkin, Mark| publisher=The Providence Journal | date=[[August 10]] [[2004]] | accessdate = 2007-01-20}}</ref>  Providence is also reputed to have the highest number of restaurants per capita,<ref>of major U.S cities</ref> many of which are founded and/or staffed by its own Johnson & Wales graduates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citytowninfo.com/places/rhode-island/providence citytowninfo.com|publisher=Moving Traffic, Inc.|title=Providence, RI|publisher=|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref>

Providence has several ethnic neighborhoods, notably [[Federal Hill, Providence, Rhode Island|Federal Hill]] and the [[Charles, Providence, Rhode Island|North End]] ([[Italy|Italian]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceri.com/Neighborhoods/charles.html providenceri.com|publisher=City of Providence|title=Charles|accessdate=2007-06-09}}</ref> [[Fox Point, Providence, Rhode Island|Fox Point]] ([[Cape Verde]]an and Portuguese),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceri.com/Neighborhoods/foxpoint.html providenceri.com|publisher=City of Providence|title = Fox Point|accessdate=2007-06-09}}</ref> [[West End, Providence, Rhode Island|West End]] (mainly Central American and Asians),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceri.com/Neighborhoods/westend.html providenceri.com|publisher=City of Providence|title = West End|accessdate=2007-06-09}}</ref> and [[Smith Hill, Providence, Rhode Island|Smith Hill]] (Irish with miscellaneous enclaves of other groups).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceri.com/Neighborhoods/smhill.html providenceri.com|publisher=City of Providence|title = Smith Hil|accessdate=2007-06-09}}</ref> There are also many dedicated community organizations and arts associations located in the city.<ref name="hist2">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2002 | url = http://www.providenceri.com/history/centuries1.html | title = Three and One-Half Centuries at a Glance | format = | work = History & Facts: America's Renaissance City | publisher = The City of Providence, Rhode Island | accessdate = 2007-01-17}}</ref>

The city gained the reputation as one of the most active and growing [[LGBT]] communities in the Northeast;<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gay.com/travel/article.html?sernum=9619 | title=Providence, R.I.: The gayest city you've driven right past | year=2007 | publisher=PLANETOUT INC. | accessdate = 2007-01-17 | author=Link, Matthew}}</ref><ref name=gay>{{cite web|url=http://www.sodomylaws.org/usa/rhode_island/rinews21.htm sodomylaws.org|title =  Gay Business Comfortable in R.I.|author = K. Alexa Mavromatis|accessdate=2007-06-09}}</ref> the rate of reported gay and lesbian relationships is 75% higher than the national average<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/gayInfo.php?locIndex=13448 epodunk.co|publisher=ePodunk Inc.|title=Providence, RI (Providence County) - city gay Index - ePodunk|accessdate=2007-06-09}}</ref> and Providence has been named among the "Best Lesbian Places to Live".<ref name=gay/> The current mayor, David Cicilline, won his election running as an openly gay man, making him the first openly gay mayor of a U.S. state capital.<ref name=firstmayor/> Former Mayor Cianci instituted the position of Mayor's Liaison to the Gay and Lesbian community in the 1990s.<ref name=gay/> There are numerous social and community organizations supporting the gay, lesbian, bisexual, and transgender community.

[[Image:Providence Cathedral, RI edited.JPG|left|thumb|[[Cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul, Providence|Providence Catholic Cathedral]] and environs]]
During the summer months, the city regularly hosts [[WaterFire]], an [[environmental art]] installation that consists of about 100 bonfires that blaze just above the surface of the three rivers that pass through the middle of downtown Providence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://waterfire.org/about-waterfire/welcome waterfire.org|title = About|publisher=waterfire.org|accessdate=2007-06-09}}</ref> There are multiple Waterfire events that are accompanied by various pieces of [[european classical music|classical]] and [[world music]]. The public art displays, most notably sculptures, change on a regular basis. 

The city is also the home of the [[Tony Awards|Tony Award]]-winning theater group [[Trinity Repertory Company]], the Providence Black Repertory Company, and the Rhode Island Philharmonic Orchestra.<ref name=culture>{{cite web|url=http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/genInfo.php?locIndex=13448|title=Providence, Rhode Island RI, city profile (Providence County)|publisher=ePodunk Inc.|accessdate=2007-06-09}}</ref> Providence is also the home of several performing arts centers such as the [[Veterans Memorial Auditorium (Providence)|Veterans Memorial Auditorium]] and the Providence Performing Arts Center. The city's underground music scene, centered around artist-run spaces such as the now-defunct [[Fort Thunder]], is known in underground music circles.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thephoenix.com/article_ektid21625.aspx | title=Keys to the Underground |publisher=Boston Phoenix | author=Fox, Andrew | date=[[August 30]] [[2006]] | accessdate = 2007-01-24}}</ref>

[[Image:20060703 Providence State House Fireworks.jpg|thumb|Fireworks at the State House during the 2006 [[4 July]] celebration]]

===Sites of interest===
[[Image:bankandchurch.JPG|thumb|Old Stone Bank and Unitarian Church]]
Providence is home to an 1200-acre park system,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.providenceri.com/government/parks/ | title=Parks Department | publisher=City of Providence | accessdate = 2007-11-08}}</ref> notably [[Waterplace Park]] and Riverwalk, [[Roger Williams Park]], [[Roger Williams National Memorial]], and [[Prospect Terrace Park]], the latter featuring expansive views of the downtown area. The East Side neighborhood of Providence includes the largest contiguous area of buildings listed on the National Register of Historic Places in the U.S. featuring many pre-revolutionary houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitnewengland.com/current_category.77/current_advcategory.234/companies_list.html?print_page=1 visitnewengland.com/|publisher=Mystic Media, Inc. and Visit New England |title=Cities of New England|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> Providence is home to the [[First Baptist Church in America]], the oldest [[Baptist]] church in the Americas, founded by [[Roger Williams]] in 1638.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fbcia.org/page116.html |publisher=fbcia.org|title=History Book|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> Nearby is Roger Williams National Memorial. Downcity Providence is home to the [[Rhode Island State House|fourth largest unsupported dome]] in the world (the second largest marble dome after St. Peter's [[Basilica]] in Rome),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rilin.state.ri.us/FactFig/ |publisher=State of Rhode Island General Assembly|title=Rhode Island Facts and Figures|accessdate = 2007-01-20}}</ref> as well as the [[Westminster Arcade]], which is the oldest enclosed shopping center in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.onetenprov.com/rhode_island_highest_homes.html from Providence Journal | title=32-story condo tower would hold R.I.'s highest homesÔøΩÔøΩ | publisher=Providence Journal | year=2007 | accessdate = 2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=125362 | title=Rhode Island State House | publisher=Emporis | year=2007 |accessdate = 2007-01-17}}</ref>

The main art museum is the [[Rhode Island School of Design Museum]], which has the twentieth largest collection in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.risd.edu/museum_membership.cfm risd.edu|title=Museum: Membership|publisher=Rhode Island School of Design|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> The city's southern waterfront hosts a decommissioned Cold War era [[Soviet submarine K-77|Russian submarine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://providenceri.com/special/sub/hours.html|title=Russian Sub in Providence|publisher=City of Providence|accessdate=2007-07-01}}</ref> In addition to the Providence Public Library and its nine branches, the city is home to the Providence Athen√¶um, the fourth oldest library in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceathenaeum.org/|publisher=Providence Athenaem|title=America's Fourth Oldest Library and Providence's Oldest Cultural Institution|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> Here, on one of his many visits to Providence, [[Edgar Allan Poe]], met and courted a love interest named [[Sarah Helen Whitman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fodors.com/miniguides/mgresults.cfm?destination=providence@124&cur_section=sig&property_id=47270|title=Providence Athenaem|publisher=Fodor's Travel|accessdate=2007-08-16}}</ref> Poe was a regular fixture there, as was [[H. P. Lovecraft]]; both of them influential writers of [[gothic horror|gothic literature]].

The [[Bank of America]] Skating Center, formerly the Fleet Skating Center, is located near Kennedy Plaza in the downtown district, connected by pedestrian tunnel to [[Waterplace Park]], a cobblestone and concrete park below street traffic that abuts Providence's three rivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceskating.com/|publisher=providenceskating.com|title=Bank of America City Center|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pps.org/great_public_spaces/one?public_place_id=86 pps.org|title=Riverwalk & Waterplace Park - Great Public Spaces|author=Lisa Palmer|publisher=Project for Public Spaces, Inc.|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref>

The southern part of the city is home to the famous roadside attraction [[Big Blue Bug|Nibbles Woodaway]] (also known as the "Big Blue Bug"), the world's largest [[termite]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebug.com/about_us.html bluebug.com|publisher=New England Pest Control|title=Who We Are|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> as well as the aforementioned Roger Williams Park, which contains a [[zoo]], a botanical center, and the Museum of Natural History and Planetarium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogerwilliamsparkzoo.org/about/main.cfm rogerwilliamsparkzoo.org|publisher=Roger Willliams Park Zoo and RI Zoological Society|title=RWP Zoo: About he Zoo|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref>

===Sports===
The city is home to the [[American Hockey League]] team [[Providence Bruins]], which plays at the [[Dunkin' Donuts Center]] (formerly the [[Providence Civic Center]]). From 1926 to 1972, the AHL's [[Providence Reds]] (renamed the Rhode Island Reds in their last years)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.azhockey.com/Pr.htm#Providence%20Reds | title=Providence Reds | date=[[October 4]] [[2005]] | publisher=A to Z Encyclopedia of Ice Hockey | accessdate = 2005-11-09}}</ref> played at the [[Rhode Island Auditorium]]. In 1972, the team relocated to the [[Dunkin' Donuts Center|Providence Civic Center]], where they played until moving to [[Binghamton, New York|Binghamton]], [[New York]], in 1977.

Providence has its own [[roller derby]] league. Formed in 2004, it currently has four teams: the Providence Mob Squad, the Sakonnet River Roller Rats, the Old Money Honeys, and the Rhode Island Riveters. The [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[New England Patriots]] and [[Major League Soccer|MLS]]'s [[New England Revolution]] play in [[Foxborough, Massachusetts|Foxborough]], [[Massachusetts]], which is situated halfway between Providence and Boston. Providence was formerly home to two major league franchises: the NFL's [[Providence Steam Roller]] in the 1920s and 1930s, and the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'s [[Providence Steamrollers]] in the 1940s. The city is also where [[Rocky Marciano]] won 29 of his 49 fights.<ref>{{cite web | author=Eisele, Andrew | url=http://boxing.about.com/od/records/a/marciano.htm | title=Rocky Marciano | publisher=About.com | year=2007 | accessdate = 2007-01-17}}</ref>

The city's defunct baseball team, the [[Providence Grays]], competed in the [[National League]] from 1879 through 1885. The team defeated the [[New York Metropolitans]] in baseball's first successful "world championship series" in [[1884 World Series|1884]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://providencegrays.org/About_Our_Project/about_our_project.html |publisher=providencegrays.org|title=About Our Project|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref> In 1914, after the [[Boston Red Sox]] purchased [[Babe Ruth]] from the then-minor league [[Baltimore Orioles (minor league)|Baltimore Orioles]], the team prepared Ruth for the major leagues by sending him to finish the season playing for a minor league team in Providence that was also known as the Grays. Today, professional baseball is offered by the [[Pawtucket Red Sox]], the AAA affiliate of the [[Boston Red Sox]] which plays in nearby [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]]. Most baseball fans &mdash; along with the local media &mdash; tend to follow the Boston Red Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/redsox/|title=Boston Red Sox|publisher=Providence Journal|accessdate=2007-06-10}}</ref>

Major colleges and universities fielding NCAA Division I athletic teams are [[Brown University]] and [[Providence College]]. The latter is a member of the [[Big East Conference]]. Much local hype is associated with games between these two schools or the [[University of Rhode Island]]. Providence has also hosted the [[Gravity Games]] alternative sports tournament during several recent summers, and was also the first host of [[ESPN]]'s [[X Games]], known in its first edition as the Extreme Games.

==Infrastructure==
===Health and medicine===
[[Image:Exitramp.JPG|thumb|right|Providence from downtown exit ramp off I-95]]
Providence is home to [[Rhode Island Hospital]], the largest general acute care hospital in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lifespan.org/rih/ | title=Rhode Island Hospital | publisher=Lifespan | year=2007 | accessdate = 2007-01-20}}</ref> The hospital is in a complex along [[Interstate 95 in Rhode Island|I-95]] that includes Hasbro Children's Hospital and Women and Infants Hospital. The city is also home to the Roger Williams Medical Center, St. Joseph Hospital For Specialty Care (a division of St. Joseph Health Services Of Rhode Island), and The Miriam Hospital, a major teaching affiliate associated with [[Brown University]]. A [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|VA]] medical center is located in Providence, as well as [[List of hospitals in Rhode Island|seven other hospitals]].

Providence is home to the [[Quality Assurance Review Center]] (QARC), which performs thousands of [[radiotherapy]] reviews per year. QARC is supported by grants from the [[National Cancer Institute]] (NCI) and the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH). It receives radiotherapy data from around one-thousand [[hospitals]] in both the [[United States]] and abroad. Over thirty-thousand cases have been reviewed at QARC since its inception in [[1977]].<ref>{{web cite|url=http://www.qarc.org/ | title=History | publisher=Quality Assurance Review Center |accessdate = 2007-01-20}}</ref> The center also maintains a strategic affiliation with the [[University of Massachusetts Medical School]] in [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]], [[Massachusetts]].

The [http://www.ribc.org/ Rhode Island Blood Center] has its main headquarters in Providence. Since 1979, the Rhode Island Blood Center has been the sole organization in charge of [[Blood donation|blood collection]] and [[blood bank|testing and distribution]] of blood products to 11 hospitals in Rhode Island.

=== Transportation ===
[[Image:Providence train station.JPG|thumb|[[Providence Station]]]]
[[Image:Providence CityHall.jpg|thumb|RIPTA buses in front of Providence City Hall]]
Providence is served by air primarily by the commercial airfield [[T. F. Green Airport]] in nearby [[Warwick, Rhode Island|Warwick]].  The [[general aviation]] fields [[North Central State Airport]], in neighboring [[Lincoln, Rhode Island|Lincoln]], [[Rhode Island]] and [[Smithfield, Rhode Island|Smithfield]], [[Rhode Island]], and [[Quonset State Airport]] in [[North Kingstown, Rhode Island|North Kingstown]], [[Rhode Island]] also serve the region.  Due to overcrowding and [[Big Dig (Boston, Massachusetts)|Big Dig]] complications in Boston, [[Massport]] has been promoting T.F. Green as an alternative to Boston's [[Logan International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.massport.com/airports/tfgreen.html Massport: Regional Airports:T.F. Green|title=T.F.Green|publisher=Massport|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref>

[[Providence (Amtrak station)|Providence Station]], located between the [[Rhode Island State House]] and the downtown district, is served by [[Amtrak]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amtrak.com/servlet/ContentServer?pagename=Amtrak/am2Station/Station_Page&code=PVD Amtrak - Stations - Providence, RI (PVD)|publisher=Amtrak|title=Providence, RI (PVD)|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref> and [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] services, with a commuter rail running to Boston.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mbta.com/schedules_and_maps/rail/lines/stations/?stopId=163 MBTA > Schedules & Maps > Commuter Rail > Providence|title=Schedules & Maps|publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref> Approximately 2400 passengers daily pass through the station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amtrak.com/pdf/AmtrakBackgroundInformationFacts-022007.pdf |format=PDF|title=Amtrak Background Information Facts|pages=2|publisher=Amtrak|accessdate=2007-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srpedd.org/03tplanch11d.pdf |format=PDF|publisher=srpedd.org|title=Chapter 11: Commuter Rail|pages=2|accessdate=2007-06-06}}</ref> Additionally, funds have been allocated to extend the commuter rail from Providence to T. F. Green Airport terminating at a [[T. F. Green Airport (MBTA station)|$222.5 million  intermodal station]] to be completed in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dot.state.ri.us/news/pages/dispNews.asp?id=237 RIDOT News - RIAC breaks ground on Warwick Intermodal Facility|Publisher=Rhode Island Department of Transportation|title=RIAC breaks ground on Warwick Intermodal Facility|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref>

[[Interstate 95 in Rhode Island|I-95]] runs from north to south through Providence while [[Interstate 195 (Rhode Island)|I-195]] connects the city to eastern Rhode Island and southeastern Massachusetts, including [[New Bedford, Massachusetts|New Bedford]], [[Massachusetts]], and [[Cape Cod]]. [[Interstate 295 (Rhode Island)|I-295]] encircles Providence while [[RI 146]] provides a direct connection with [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]], [[Massachusetts]]. The city has commissioned and begun a long-term project, the [[Iway]], to move I-195 not only for safety reasons, but also to free up land and to reunify the Jewelry District with Downcity Providence, which had been split from one another by the highway.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dot.state.ri.us/projects/construction/195intro.htm | title=Relocating I-195 in Providence | year=2007 | publisher=Rhode Island Department of Transportation |accessdate = 2007-01-20}} </ref>  The project is estimated to cost $446 million and be completed in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providence.edu/polisci/students/indiapointpark/195background.html | title =195 Relocation Background|Publisher=Providence College|accessdate=2007-05-26}}</ref>

[[Kennedy Plaza]], in downtown Providence, serves as a transportation hub for local public transit as well as a departure point for [[Peter Pan Bus Lines|Peter Pan]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.peterpanbus.com/tickets/terminals.php#RI |publisher=Peter Pan Bus LInes| title=Tickets - Terminal Listings|accessdate = 2007-06-05}}</ref> and [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greyhound.com/scripts/en/TicketCenter/terminal.asp?city=050028&PrinterFriendly=true&BackPage=/scripts/en/TicketCenter/locations.asp?State=ri Greyhound.com|title=Greyhound: Providence, Rhode Island|publisher=Greyhound Lines, Inc.|accessdate = 2007-06-05}}</ref> bus lines. Public transit is managed by [[Rhode Island Public Transit Authority]] (RIPTA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ripta.com/ ripta.com|title=RIPTA|publisher=Rhode Island Public Transportation Authority|accessdate=2007-06-05}}</ref> Through RIPTA alone Kennedy Plaza serves over 71,000 people a day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ripta.com/content1477.html ripta.com|publisher=Rhode Island Public Transportation Authority|title=RIPTA Accomplishments in FY2006|accessdate=2007-06-06}} 25,943,883 boardings / 365 days = 71,079 daily.</ref> The majority of the area covered by RIPTA is served by traditional buses. Of particular note is the [[East Side Trolley Tunnel]] running under College Hill, the use of which is reserved for RIPTA buses. RIPTA also operates the ''Providence LINK'', a system of [[tourist trolley]]s in downtown Providence, as well as a ferry to [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]] between May and October.[[Image:b4sunset.jpg|thumb|left|Early construction on the [[Iway]] 195 relocation project from across the [[Narragansett Bay]]]]

=== Utilities ===
Electricity and natural gas are provided by [[National Grid USA|Narragansett Electric Company]] which is owned by National Grid USA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/business/content/projo_20060217_grid17.1d64dbea.html|publisher=Providence Journal|title=Electric utility buying R.I. gas company|author=David McPherson|accessdate=2007-06-25}}</ref> Providence Water is responsible for the distribution of drinking water, ninety percent of which comes from the [[Scituate Reservoir]] about ten miles west of downtown, with contributions coming from four smaller bodies of water.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.provwater.com/introduction.htm|title=Introduction|Providence Water Introduction|publisher=Providence Water|accessdate=2007-06-25}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.provwater.com/watershed.htm|title=Providence Water Watershed|publisher=Providence Water|accessdate=2007-06-25}}</ref>

== Sister cities ==
Providence has four [[Town twinning|sister cities]] designated by [[Sister Cities International]]:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.providenceri.com/press/sister_city.html | title=Mayor Announces Sister City - Meeting (7/30/2003) | publisher=Providence, RI, Office of the Mayor|accessdate = 2007-01-17}}</ref>
*{{flagicon|Cambodia}} [[Phnom Penh]], [[Cambodia]]
*{{flagicon|Italy}} [[Florence]], [[Italy]] 
*{{flagicon|Latvia}} [[Riga]], [[Latvia]] 
*{{flagicon|Dominican Republic}} [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]

